Pundits and politicians described the carnage as the product of ancient hatreds, in a land of primitive ultra-nationalists who were now free to indulge in a timeless cycle of bloodlust and vengeance. But not long before, Yugoslavia had been viewed by many as one of the more successful states of the socialist world. The country maintained generally harmonious relations with the West, its citizens enjoyed material comforts and political freedoms unparalleled elsewhere in Eastern Europe/the Balkans, and the national groups lived in relative peace. How then, did Yugoslavia come to such a violent and dramatic end? How did the country founded on the idea of brotherhood and unity explode into the worst bloodshed seen in Europe since World War II?   Aims: This class aims to unpack many of the explanations that are used to explain and analyze the apparent persistence of nationalism and violence in the Balkans. We will work to understand the historical and political context in which national ideas (re?)-emerged in postwar Yugoslavia, and to understand the myths and agendas that underlay the different nationalist discourses. We will understand the national tensions of Yugoslavia as part of the broader socio-political context of postwar Europe, also examining national and majority/minority tensions elsewhere in Eastern Europe, and in Western Europe. Finally, we will turn our attention to the collapse of Yugoslavia in the 1990s, with the intent of understanding it not as the inevitable explosion of ancient hatreds, but rather as a historical event contingent on the actions of specific groups and individuals. While this course will draw on numerous works of scholarly literature, the most important focus will be on the regions rich body of films and novels, which we will use to better understand the various cultural, intellectual, and political factors at play in the postwar period. Pundits and politicians described the carnage as the product of ancient hatreds, in a land of primitive ultra-nationalists who were now free to indulge in a timeless cycle of bloodlust and vengeance. But not long before, Yugoslavia had been viewed by many as one of the more successful states of the socialist world. The country maintained generally harmonious relations with the West, its citizens enjoyed material comforts and political freedoms unparalleled elsewhere in Eastern Europe/the Balkans, and the national groups lived in relative peace. How then, did Yugoslavia come to such a violent and dramatic end? How did the country founded on the idea of brotherhood and unity explode into the worst bloodshed seen in Europe since World War II?   Aims: This class aims to unpack many of the explanations that are used to explain and analyze the apparent persistence of nationalism and violence in the Balkans. We will work to understand the historical and political context in which national ideas (re?)-emerged in postwar Yugoslavia, and to understand the myths and agendas that underlay the different nationalist discourses. We will understand the national tensions of Yugoslavia as part of the broader socio-political context of postwar Europe, also examining national and majority/minority tensions elsewhere in Eastern Europe, and in Western Europe. Finally, we will turn our attention to the collapse of Yugoslavia in the 1990s, with the intent of understanding it not as the inevitable explosion of ancient hatreds, but rather as a historical event contingent on the actions of specific groups and individuals. While this course will draw on numerous works of scholarly literature, the most important focus will be on the regions rich body of films and novels, which we will use to better understand the various cultural, intellectual, and political factors at play in the postwar period.
